title: For Sale:  Ithaca 1911 45 ACP US Army Combat Pistol
postcontent: Here’s my dad’s 45 that he carried overseas during the Korean War. As you can see he couldn’t resist putting target sights on it. Of course they can be replaced with the original style sight for authenticity purposes if you prefer.There is so much history behind this pistol it would fill a novel.As you can see from the excerpt from a Gun Collectors Magazine (below) these guns are highly collectable and going for quite a bit of money in the original box and in excellent condition.Some History from Gun Collectors Magazine"During WWII, Colt had orders for more pistols from the military than it could handle, so they set up Ithaca as subcontractors for the huge order. With tips, drawings, and help from Colt, Ithaca churned out no less than 369,129 pattern M1911 guns for Uncle Sam between 1943-1945. They got so good at making these guns in fact, that the military gave them a special letter of appreciation after the company improved the standard manufacturing procedure for the triggers. These guns today are a hit with collectors, running as high as $2600 a pop for guns still in excellent condition with the original cardboard shipping carton."I have seen these historic firearms, like my dad’s, going for an average of $1685 and the most expensive I’ve seen on the market was $6899.Other than not having the original box and the target sight being installed, this gun is in excellent, original, as manufactured condition. You can see some machining marks on it, but that's from the original manufacturing process, Not after the fact, which some say adds to the historic value and provenance.I'm asking $1595 or best offer for this historic 45.
